node.text: I really loved the post you just deleted about what it takes to become a sex educator—and as well any kind of teacher or leader in these worlds. So many people fronting on social media days. Too little people putting in the years of work. Respect ❤️
@primadora_ I’m working my way through that one too 👏🏽

I’ve lost so many hours of my life to thoughts that there is something wrong with me; that my body is faulty; that my orgasm, arousal, sexuality is broken because it doesn’t look the way it “should”. This thought has seeped into the sexual experiences I’ve had with others. It has poisoned the intimacy between me & my lovers. It has stripped me from my power with that harmful notion that as a sexual person, I am not enough.

The sexual standards our culture (and we ourselves) has largely measured us against—how fast we’re supposed to come, how aroused we’re supposed to get, how easily our desire is supposed to arrive—is man-made, literally.

For hundreds of years, cis-man sexuality has been the dominant default to the extent that the perfectly normal nuances & unique manifestations of our (those of us who a not cis-men) own sexuality have been deemed immature, complicated, damaged.

But there is beauty in having this information. It means that there is literally nothing wrong with you, that you are not broken. What is broken is the patriarchal system that is being used to judge & quantify your sexuality. This system doesn’t serve you, it doesn’t want you to thrive. It wants to keep you small. And you don’t have to believe that shit anymore. You can release it & choose how you want your sexuality to be actualized. You can choose to celebrate your sexuality as it is now. And that choosing is a giant fuck-you to those oppressive systems because liberating yourself from the insidious clutches of these beliefs is an act of resistance.

You’ve probably heard that May is Masturbation month—which is honestly the perfect time to practice and embody new stories about your sexuality through the way you hold space for your pleasure, to use solo sex magic to reprogram the way you access and make space for your sexuality, to deepen your connection with your body and erotic energy on your own terms.

What systems of oppression regarding your sexuality do you want to unlearn? What new intentions about your sexuality do you want to reclaim? And what will you do this month to begin that healing/liberation journey, step by step?

Here with you. 🧡

My meditation just this afternoon was me taking a phrase I hear too often in my negative self talk: “I am too sexual”, and converting it to “My sexuality is powerful”. I am through with the shame surrounding femme, non-binary, & trans erotic power. What feels good is what is right. 💖

I am unlearning patriarchal oppression surrounding sexuality by having recently ‘come out’ as asexual. Finally speaking my truth has breathed so much power back into who I am as an autonomous woman; it is that autonomy which goes *directly against* the patriarchy and the ones who thrive on us being submissive in any form. It took me nearly ten years to face it and choke down the shame I felt surrounding it. I still find myself wanting to defend it when it doesn’t merit defending! In our cis-male dominated world you’re only of value if you want to be sexual on their terms. God forbid it be your own. We are judged by our sexual appetites, however prevalent or absent they may be. My new intentions regarding my sexuality is to drive home the fact that there is nothing wrong with mine nor anyone else’s sexual orientation or appetites, regardless how different they may look to one another. We are not broken, dirty, or damaged. Healing for me will probably include speaking out about it every day, regardless how annoying that may be to my followers or friends 😅

At the age of 35 I am finally becoming comfortable with my femininity and sexuality. I’m still learning to break from the idea that a woman is to be delicate and not so vocal. That isn’t me, and I no longer can fake it anymore in order to make others comfortable. My peace and my own understanding are what matter the most to me now as I soon journey into year 36 with my two sons in tote.
